<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think the focus needs to be kept not on what you can do that will help the other players, but on what only you can do to npc's that will benefit the group. Wizard has never been a support class. imo they never should be. There are plenty of other ways to improve group desireablity.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
While I'm sure many will agree with your feeling here, in keeping with a wizards offensive nature, it's just not true.  There are classes in the game right now that can do little for a group and a great deal to a mob.  Necromancers, Wizards, Mages, Rogues...  All of these have a hard time finding groups, with the grouping edge till PoP going to Rogue, and starting to drift back that way too--due to mana constraints and the fact that rogues don't need it.  <br>
<br>
If you have nothing to offer the group, then your going to be the second thing anyone wants, Period.  This has been shown over and over again in the games history.  Of the pure casters, the only one wanted in groups is Enchanter, precisely because they can Haste and Clarity.  It does not hurt that they can Slow either, especially in PoP--they have all the utility, and fair nuking power too, though they rarely use it.  Clerics have the best heals, and untill PoP ruled the healing world, Now Shamans are pushing them aside with their slows, and Druids are left in the breeze except as backup, or charm in the few places it works.  What you can do for the group is indeed what causes group desireability and it's a major shortcoming of the game that all the utility was given to a very few classes. <p><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=448514">Antrygus Windrose </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=faramir42>Faramir42</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 65<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/30/03 7:56 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: spells</span><hr size=1> Wizards don't have to be just a nuking class. There is much you can do that isn't nuking, and can help the group, and I'm not talking buffs. <br>
<br>
First, when ever I am grouped with an enchanter, and we get adds, instead of nuking the mob the tank is on, I root and snare the mobs after the enchanter has mezzed them. Generally, what happens is he uses an AE mezz, and i use an AE snare. Then he goes back and uses single mezzes on them, and I root them. This way, should any wake up, they will be rooted, and if the root breaks, they will be snared anyway. This saves the enchanter from having to mezz and root and increase his aggro, making it harder for the tank to get aggro off him when he has to break the mezz. <br>
<br>
By the time this done, the tank has done about one bubble of damage and has lots of aggro. I then start my attacks, standing very close to the tank, in case I get aggro by accident. That way he doesn't have to run around trying to find the mob.<br>
<br>
I always have at least one stun loaded. And I've used it to save lives. There have been fights where we didn't have our enchanter with us, and the tank took lots of damage. I would see the complete heal message, and I would hit the mob with a stun, buying the cleric about 4-6 seconds to get his heal off. It also works when the cleric is getting attacked. I will switch targets, stun the mob, and then root it. <br>
<br>
And of course, our stun spells and force strike spells are great for stoping casting and healing mobs. Generally speaking, outside of boss mobs, those that do cast and heal don't have the hit points of melee mobs. So I switch rolls and focus more on stopping it from casting and healing. By the time it trying to heal, the aggro is fully on the tank, and I'm not worried that my stun is gonna get me killed. Stun, Nuke, dead. <br>
<br>
Two wizards in a group, with two stuns up each, can keep a mob standing there for a long time doing nothing. I normally group with another wizard, and we have a whole system worked out. <br>
<br>
There is much that a wizard can do for a group. Even if the group doesn't realize what they are doing, besides burning down a mob.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=necridious>Necridious</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 326<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/30/03 6:39 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: spells</span><hr size=1> I know that, and you know that.  There is something to be said for root and snare, and using stuns.<br>
